"\t\t     and XP Professional)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:19
msgid "INTRODUCTION"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:26
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tOnce I had my shiny LFS system I wanted to be with it all the time. I\n"
"wanted to work on it from work, from my girlfriend's house, from school,\n"
"everywhere. So I went out and read some documentation on how to set up "
"OpenSSH\n"
"(including Daniel's hint on\n"
"http://hints.linuxfromscratch.org/hints/openssh.txt). Here's a summary of "
"what\n"
"I came up with. I hope it helps you out and that you learn from it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:29
msgid "DISCLAIMER"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:37
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tJust like the one the great Kevin Smith has at the beginning of Dogma\n"
"(go watch that movie if you have no idea what I'm talking about). Please "
"make\n"
"sure you know what you are doing (or at least have an idea of what you are\n"
"doing) when you follow this hint. The author cannot be made responsible for "
"any\n"
"missed configuration, run-over cats, hair loss or any other problem that "
"arises\n"
"directly or indirectly from following the simple instructions stated "
"here. Now\n"
"that we got that out of the way, let's move on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:39
msgid "SETTING UP THE SERVER\t"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tFirst of all, in order to make your machine more secure you need to\n"
"disable the regular telnet daemon and make sure that OpenSSH gets started "
"at\n"
"bootup (read Daniel's hint on how to do this). Once you have a running "
"OpenSSH\n"
"fire up your favorite editor to change its configuration (the file in my "
"system\n"
"is /etc/ssh/sshd_config).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tMake sure that the following options are set (1):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:53
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tIgnoreRhosts no\n"
"\tRhostsAuthentication no\n"
"\tRhostsRSAAuthentication yes\n"
"\tRSAAuthentication yes\n"
"\tPasswordAuthentication no\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tOptionally, you can set this line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tProtocol 2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:60
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tTo make sure your server always uses the (more secure) version 2 "
"protocol.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:68
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tWhat you are doing with these options is telling sshd to make sure that\n"
"all the people trying to log into your system have a valid encryption key "
"and\n"
"not to allow login with a simple username/password combination. What this "
"means\n"
"is that your users  will need to create a new key pair for themselves in "
"your\n"
"system and they will need to have their file key handy (in a floppy or "
"copied\n"
"into their laptop) whenever they want to log into the system. This might "
"sound\n"
"a little cumbersome but the increased security is well worth it in my "
"opinion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tPlease make sure you read the Domain mini-HOWTO (1) if you want to\n"
"learn how to do do some other tricks (such as tunneling X over the "
"connection)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:73
msgid "CREATING YOUR PRIVATE/PUBLIC KEY COMBO"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:77
msgid ""
"This is the part of this hint where configuration varies slightly is you use "
"Protocol v1 or v2. To create an RSA key for v1, the user has to type this "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "        ssh-keygen -b 1024 -f new_rsa_key\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:84
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tThis command will create two files in the curent directory: new_rsa_key\n"
"and new_rsa_key.pub. The first file is the private key and the second is "
"the\n"
"public key (hence the .pub extension :). This key pair is v1 by default, "
"read\n"
"on to create a v2 key.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tFor a v2 key, the key has to be created using PuTTYgen, available from\n"
"the same place PuTTY is (2). Start up PuTTYgen and select SSH2 RSA as the "
"type\n"
"of key you want to generate. Click on Generate and follow the instructions\n"
"while you wait for your key pair to be created. Once it's done, copy the "
"text\n"
"that's supposed to go into your authorized_keys2 file, and save it into a "
"file.\n"
"This is your public key. Click on Save private key and keep that file "
"somewhere\n"
"handy. We'll come back to it. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tUsing either method, the user will be asked for a pass phrase.\n"
"Make_sure_this_is_not_blank. Doing that would mean that if someone found "
"the\n"
"private key they would be able to use it to gain easy acces to your "
"system.\n"
"Now have them copy the public key file into their "
"$HOME/.ssh/authorized_keys\n"
"file for v1 or $HOME/.ssh/authorized_keys2 for v2. (You can simply type "
"'cat\n"
"new_rsa_key.pub >> $HOME/.ssh/authorized_keys (or) authorized_keys2' "
"depending\n"
"on the protocol version you are using).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:102
msgid "CREATING YOUR PORTABLE CLIENT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tNow the fun part. Copy the private key (new_rsa_key, or the one you\n"
"saved from PuTTYgen) file into a floppy and also put a copy of PuTTY (2), "
"the\n"
"great ssh client for Windows, into the same floppy. Configure PuTTY with "
"your\n"
"server parameters, etc. Make sure you select the appropiate protocol "
"version\n"
"and that you point to the private key you saved before.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:113
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tPuTTY saves the fingerprint of every host it connects to in the Windows\n"
"registry to make sure that you are connecting to a host that has confirmed "
"its\n"
"\"identity\" with you. The only downside to this is that you are not able "
"to\n"
"carry this information with you, at least not easily.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tHere's what to do to save that information (as well as any changes you\n"
"make to the PuTTY configuration) and have it ready on the go. You can "
"either\n"
"follow the instructions from the PuTTY authors and create a batch file "
"with\n"
"some .reg files (3), or you can download a small VB program I wrote "
"(4). The\n"
"difference between the two methods is that my program works between "
"different\n"
"versions of Windows, since starting with Win2K, the files exported from "
"the\n"
"registry are Unicode as opposed to regular ANSI files. This prevents older\n"
"versions of Windows from importing files that come from Win2K and WinXP\n"
"machines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tPlease be aware that using any of these two methods (a batch file or my\n"
"little program) might cause your current settings to be deleted from the\n"
"registry. (Well, ahem, at least *my* program warns you if that might happen "
":)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:129
msgid "CONCLUSION"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/openssh_remote_floppy.txt:133
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tLike I said at the beginning; I hope that you learned from this hint\n"
"and that it helps you have a far more secured server. Feel free to contact "
"me\n"
"if you have any questions. I will try to answer the best I can.\n"
msgstr ""

